The '''magnetic diffusivity''' is a parameter in [[plasma physics]] which appears in the [[magnetic Reynolds number]]. It has SI units of m²/s and is defined as:<ref>W. Baumjohann and R. A. Treumann, ''Basic Space Plasma Physics'', Imperial College Press, 1997.</ref> :<math>\eta = \frac{1}{\mu_0 \sigma_0}</math>, while in Gaussian units it can be defined as :<math>\eta = \frac{c^2}{4\pi\sigma_0}</math>. In the above, <math>\mu_0</math> is the [[vacuum permeability|permeability of free space]], <math>c</math> is the speed of light, and <math>\sigma_0</math> is the [[electrical conductivity]] of the material in question. In case of a plasma, this is the conductivity due to [[Coulomb collision|Coulomb]] or neutral collisions: <math>\sigma_0=\frac{n_ee^2}{m_e\nu_c}</math>, where * <math>n_e</math> is the [[electron]] [[density]]. * <math>e</math> is the [[elementary charge|electron charge]]. * <math>m_e</math> is the electron [[mass]]. * <math>\nu_c</math> is the collision frequency.
==See also== {{colbegin}} * [[Electrical resistivity and conductivity]] {{colend}}
